metadata.name: Canyon #102
metadata.description:
Canyon is a generative art project inspired by canyons and reinterpreted in 9 different styles (that each have their own specificities):
- Grand Canyon
- Radioactive
- Blue Grotto
- Black Crystals
- Magma
- Iceberg
- Imagination
- UV
- Sandstone

Accessories (Kayak, Rowing Boat, Barrels) are present on some variations (in this case, it is possible to generate a second variation without accessories by pressing "a").

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Sand #82
metadata.description:
This project is a cellular automata that simulates falling sand. The falling is deterministic: each sand particle will fall to the same place each time the program is run. Some iterations eventually stop, some continue indefinitely.

The fun is that the project is implemented on a fragment shader. There is no array of grains of sand. Each pixel decides whether a grain of sand from a neighboring pixel will end up in it or not. This logic required a lot of banging my head against the wall, because the slightest mistake caused sand to disappear into nowhere or appear out of nothing and clutter up the entire space.

0…9 — set speed
space — pause
s — save picture
drag over — add more sand
shift+drag — erase

metadata.name: Anachronous #269
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: The Shadows of Shallows #68
metadata.description:
I like fishing.
I like to find fish swimming in the shallows.
I was inspired by the waterfront.

I used fallen leaves and goldfish as motifs on the canvas.
The surface and bottom of the water.
Shadows of leaves and fish overlap.

The fewer the pieces, the rarer they are.

Enjoy!
